        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-04-18T23:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-04-18T23:00:00-05:00" n="297" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d297">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/4–1949: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister-Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Clark</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Canton</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-04-19T12:00:00+08:00">April 19, 1949—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received April 19—3:41 a.
                        m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Cantel 234. George Yeh, Acting Foreign Minister, says press reports Communist
                    peace terms founded [<hi rend="italic">unfounded?</hi>]; that they are of course
                    unacceptable, and that in this connection he returning Nanking April 22, but
                    expects be back Canton within “short time”. Tung Lin, other Vice Minister, will
                    return Canton prior departure Yeh.</p>
                <p>Sent Department Cantel 234; repeated Nanking 203, Shanghai 150.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Clark</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
